# WGPL — Git rules for AI agents

These rules apply whenever an AI agent creates commits or interacts with git in this repo.

## Commits

- **Only create commits when the user explicitly asks** (e.g. "commit", "hacé commit").
- **Never add `Co-authored-by` trailers** — in particular not `Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>`.
  The commit author must reflect the human maintainer only.
- If the environment auto-injects a `Co-authored-by` trailer after `git commit`, rewrite the commit
  without that trailer (e.g. `git commit-tree` with the same tree, parent, and message body).
- Follow Conventional Commits and [CONTRIBUTING.md — Commit messages](../CONTRIBUTING.md#commit-messages).
- Do not reference internal session artifacts in commit messages: plan/todo slugs, audit IDs,
  debt wave labels (`v1.0`, `v1.2`, `ola v1.x`), or debt item IDs (`D3`, `D16`, etc.).
  Those are planning control — not semver, not git tags. Describe product/code changes only.

## Push and remote

- **Never run `git push`** (nor `git push -u`, force-push, or publish to remote) **unless the user explicitly asks**.
- After a local commit, stop and report status; let the user decide when to push.
- Do not assume "push" from phrases like "ship it" unless push is stated clearly.

## Pull requests

- Create PRs only when the user explicitly asks.
- When creating a PR, push only if needed and only with explicit user approval for push.
